HEADWORD: Apotheosis
<hw>Ap`o*the"o*sis</hw> <pr>(⟦acr⟧p`⟦osl⟧*th⟦emac⟧"⟦osl⟧*s⟦icr⟧s;
277)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos> <plw>Apotheoses</plw>
<pr>(⟦acr⟧p`⟦osl⟧*th⟦emac⟧"⟦osl⟧*s⟦emac⟧z)</pr>. <ety>[L., fr. Gr.
<grk>'apoqe`wsis</grk>, fr. <grk>'apoqewy^n</grk> to deify;
<grk>'apo`</grk> from + <grk>qewy^n</grk> to deify, <grk>qeo`s</grk> a
god.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of elevating a mortal to the rank
of, and placing him among, ⟦ldquo⟧the gods;⟦rdquo⟧
deification.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Glorification; exaltation.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The
<xex>apotheosis</xex> of chivalry.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Prescott.</au> ⟦ldquo⟧The
noisy <xex>apotheosis</xex> of liberty and machinery.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>F.
Harrison.</au>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Apotheosize</ent>⟦br⟧
